  "text": "All Aβ PET scans were acquired using a PET/CT scanner (GE Healthcare, Milwaukee, Wisconsin) operating in 3D mode. Subjects were injected with Pittsburgh Compound B (PiB) (average, 614 MBq; range, and after a 40 min uptake period a 20 min PiB scan was obtained consisting of four 5-min dynamic frames following a low dose CT transmission scan. Standard corrections were applied. The automated anatomical labeling (AAL) atlas [CITATION_1] was used to calculate median PiB uptake for 6 cortical regions-of-interest (ROIs) which were each divided by median cerebellar uptake to create uptake ratios. A cortical-to-cerebellar (SUVR) ratio was formed by calculating median uptake ratio values across all 6 regions. Patients were classified as Aβ (+) using a SUVR ratio cut-point of 1.5 [CITATION_2] . Visual assessment of all Aβ PET scans was also performed (VJL and JLW) to verify Aβ status. The visual assessment and SUVR agreed in all but two cases which were visually read as positive but had low SUVR ratios. These cases were considered Aβ (+) in subsequent analyses and were excluded from analyses that utilized the actual SUVR value.",
